<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,514,1436]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,328,626,652]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The species is closest to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Simon)" baseAuthorityName="Simon" box="[626,894,626,652]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Maso" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis box="[626,792,626,651]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Maso gallicus</emphasis>
(Simon)
</taxonomicName>
but differs by its smaller size, the cone on the cymbium with two clavate spines (three in 
<taxonomicName box="[656,788,664,689]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Maso" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis box="[656,788,664,689]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">M. gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the circular embolus (
<figureCitation box="[1110,1198,664,690]" captionStart="FIGURES 43–56" captionStartId="25.[151,269,1778,1802]" captionText="FIGURES 43–56. Figs 43–46. Erigonoplus nasutus (O.P.-Cambridge, 1875); 43. Male prosoma, lateral view; 44. Male palp, prolateral view; 45. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 46. Embolic division, anteroventral view. Figs 47–49. Maso douro Bosmans &amp; Cardoso new species; 47. Male palp, prolateral view, with denticulate hairs in detail; 48. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 49. Embolic division, anterior view. Figs 50-56. Mecopisthes crassirostris (Simon, 1884); 50. Male prosoma, lateral view; 51. Idem, dorsal view; 52. Male palp, prolateral view; 53. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 54. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 55. Epigynum, ventral view; 56. Vulva, ventral view (E = embolus; StA = suprategular apophysis; Tp = tailpiece)." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,514,1436]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,310,701,727]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Remark:</emphasis>
The characters of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1884" box="[679,744,701,726]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Maso" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[679,744,701,726]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Maso</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[765,817,701,727]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Westring, 1851" authorityName="Westring" authorityYear="1851" box="[935,1331,701,727]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Maso" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sundevalli">
<emphasis box="[935,1133,701,726]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Maso sundevalli</emphasis>
Westring, 1851
</taxonomicName>
) are the unmodified prosoma, the position of the metatarsal trichobothria (Mt&gt; 0.9), the presence of two longitudinal rows of stout ventral spines on the tibiae (
<bibRefCitation author="Wiehle, H." box="[639,794,776,802]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 620" refId="ref45615" refString="Wiehle, H. (1960) Spinnentiere oder Arachnoidea (Araneae). XI. Micryphantidae-Zwergspinnen. Tierwelt Deutschlands 47, i - xi, 1 - 620." type="journal article" year="1960">Wiehle 1960</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Locket, G. H. &amp; Millidge, A. F." box="[805,1092,776,802]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" refId="ref44518" refString="Locket, G. H. &amp; Millidge, A. F. (1953) British Spiders, Volume II Ray Society, London." type="book" year="1953">Locket &amp; Millidge 1953</bibRefCitation>
) and the embolus in the form of a coil or part of a coil (
<bibRefCitation author="Millidge, A. F." box="[455,629,813,839]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 60" refId="ref44764" refString="Millidge, A. F. (1977) The conformation of the male palpal organs of Linyphiid spiders, and its application to the taxonomic and phylogenetic analysis of the family (Araneae: Linyphiidae). Bulletin of the British Arachnological Society, 4, 1 - 60." type="journal article" year="1977">Millidge 1977</bibRefCitation>
). The position of this new species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1884" box="[1188,1253,813,838]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Maso" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1188,1253,813,838]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Maso</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is problematic, as only the characters of the male palp point to it. There is a strong resemblance to 
<taxonomicName box="[1179,1351,850,875]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Maso" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis box="[1179,1351,850,875]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Maso gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence in the male palp of a strong dorsal cymbial tubercle, clavate hairs on the tibia and a circular embolus. At the moment, and in absence of the female, the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1884" box="[809,874,925,950]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Maso" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[809,874,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Maso</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fits the species best.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,514,1436]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,352,962,988]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Description:</emphasis>
Male: Measurements: Total length 1.1, prosoma 0.51 long, 0.43 wide. Colour: Prosoma yellowish orange, slightly suffused with grey; legs yellowish orange, patellae and basal and distal parts of tibiae whitish; abdomen pale grey. Prosoma: Unmodified, unless for a small pit behind the PL, smaller than the eye’s diameter; in lateral view with median concavity. Eyes: Relatively small; a = 0.33, b = 1.5, c = 2, d = 1.5. Chelicerae: Fang groove with 4 promarginal and 2 retromarginal teeth. Legs: L Sp Ti I = 0.4; P Sp Ti I = 0.1; Mt I broken off; Tb Mt II = 0.3; Tb Mt IV absent. Palp (
<figureCitation box="[851,988,1149,1175]" captionStart="FIGURES 43–56" captionStartId="25.[151,269,1778,1802]" captionText="FIGURES 43–56. Figs 43–46. Erigonoplus nasutus (O.P.-Cambridge, 1875); 43. Male prosoma, lateral view; 44. Male palp, prolateral view; 45. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 46. Embolic division, anteroventral view. Figs 47–49. Maso douro Bosmans &amp; Cardoso new species; 47. Male palp, prolateral view, with denticulate hairs in detail; 48. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 49. Embolic division, anterior view. Figs 50-56. Mecopisthes crassirostris (Simon, 1884); 50. Male prosoma, lateral view; 51. Idem, dorsal view; 52. Male palp, prolateral view; 53. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 54. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 55. Epigynum, ventral view; 56. Vulva, ventral view (E = embolus; StA = suprategular apophysis; Tp = tailpiece)." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Figs 47–49</figureCitation>
): Tibia with large, rounded retrolateral apophysis, pointed terminally; cymbium with strong anterior tubercle, with one dorsal and one retrolateral clavate spine, as in 
<taxonomicName box="[395,568,1224,1249]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Maso" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis box="[395,568,1224,1249]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Maso gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; paracymbium with basal, curved spine; tailpiece long and elongated; embolus circular, describing slightly more than one circle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,514,1436]" box="[198,430,1298,1324]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,299,1298,1324]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Female:</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
